ce:section.ce:para:
For sensing applications, a range of N-CD-based nanoanalytical sensors have been developed to enable selective and sensitive detection of various metal ions and small molecules [41]. Ethylenediamine (EN), a water-soluble cationic polyelectrolyte, has been widely used in the fields of catalysis [42], gene delivery [43], fiber modification [44], separation and wastewater adsorption [45], and sensing [46]. In the last few years, EN was also widely used in the preparation of N-CDs. EN doping improves the optical and electronic properties, fluorescent behavior, surface modification, and chemical activity of CDs. The research presented here involved the surface modifying EN on controlled, low-cost, and facile one-step hydrothermalization of wastepaper to produce a solution-based zero-dimensional carbon nanodots (CDs/en), which was then applied as a luminous probe for sensitive and rapid detection of Hg(II) (Scheme 1
                     ). The as-synthesized CDs/en-based optical probe was constructed with two signals: fluorescence intensity and absorbance variation. Compared with most CD-based sensors for Hg(II) detection (Table 1
                     ), our method furnishes some significant superiority. First, the majority of documented CD-based sensors produce a single-mode output [47]. It is generally known that the bi-mode output increases the credibility of data. The fluorescence changes, in particular, are easy and transparent in our work. Second, the design of the sensor is simple and inexpensive. Song et al. [48] used nanomaterials to achieve dual-mode detection of Hg(II), which increased the experimental difficulty and economic cost due to the synthesis of Ag, Au, and Pt nanoparticles. Third, a transient reaction time and lower detection limit are other advantages of the proposed assay. Our study found that Hg(II) detection can be measured in just 1 min at room temperature, which makes the detection process more efficient. Additionally, the lower detection limit was ascertained to be 0.16 nM. These outstanding properties of CDs/en, combined with their easy preparation, make them a promising material for optical probes. Remarkably, the as-prepared CDs/en can accomplish dual tasks through fluorescence and absorbance “turn off” bi-mode readout for Hg(II) detection.
